Yes. After setting up **MySQL Master–Slave replication**, you can access the database through a **web interface** instead of the terminal. The easiest way is to install **phpMyAdmin** with a web server like **Apache HTTP Server** on your **Amazon EC2 instance**. This lets you manage MySQL from a browser. 🌐
Below is the **complete procedure**.

# 1️⃣ Install Apache Web Server
Run on the server where you want web access (usually the **master server**).

sudo apt update
sudo apt install apache2 -y

Start Apache: 

sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2

Test it in the browser:http://MASTER_PUBLIC_IP

If Apache works, you will see the **Apache default page**.
---
# 2️⃣ Install PHP and MySQL Extension

sudo apt install php php-mysql php-mbstring php-zip php-gd php-json php-curl -y

Restart Apache:
 
sudo systemctl restart apache2

# 3️⃣ Install phpMyAdmin

sudo apt install phpmyadmin -y

During installation:
1. Select **apache2** (to select space+a, press tab for ok enter)
2. Choose **Yes** for database configuration
3. Enter a password for phpMyAdmin
---
# 4️⃣ Enable phpMyAdmin in Apache
Run:

sudo phpenmod mbstring
sudo systemctl restart apache2

Then link phpMyAdmin to Apache:

sudo ln -s /usr/share/phpmyadmin /var/www/html/phpmyadmin

Restart Apache again:

sudo systemctl restart apache2

# 5️⃣ Open EC2 Security Group
In **Amazon EC2 security group**, add this rule:
| Port | Protocol | Source    |
| ---- | -------- | --------- |
| 80   | TCP      | 0.0.0.0/0 |
This allows web access.

# 6️⃣ Access MySQL from Browser
Open your browser: http://MASTER_PUBLIC_IP/phpmyadmin
Login using:
Username: admin
Password: StrongPassword@123

Now you will see the **MySQL databases in a web interface**.
You can:
* Create databases
* Create tables
* Run SQL queries
* View replication data---

# 7️⃣ Test Replication from Web
1. In phpMyAdmin (master), create a database:
mysql>

CREATE DATABASE testweb;

2. Check the slave server:
mysql>

SHOW DATABASES;

You should see **testweb**, confirming replication works.
